The Daily Routine (what you should actually do)

You don’t need to “study” the project.
You need to internalize three layers:

How it works (mechanics)

Why it works that way (trade-offs)

What would break if changed (invariants)

Do this 15–20 minutes a day.

Layer 1 — Mechanics (How)

Every day, you should be able to explain these without looking:

Architecture (in 30 seconds)

Say this out loud:

Browser is a React SPA. It never calls GitHub directly.
All requests go through a Next.js API gateway.
The gateway validates token + session against Redis.
If allowed, it fetches markdown from GitHub and returns it.

If you can’t say this smoothly → you’re not ready.

Identity Model

You must know this cold:

x-dev-token → who you are

x-session-id → which browser

Redis:

token:<token>:active_session

quota keys

This is core to your system.

Layer 2 — Reasoning (Why)

This is what interviewers care about more than code.

You should be able to answer:

Why backend gating?

To prevent exposing GitHub tokens and to control access, enforce quotas, and prevent abuse.

Why session locking?

To prevent token sharing across browsers.

Why Redis?

Fast, TTL support, simple atomic counters, perfect for quotas and locks.

Why pre-check + post-consume?

So we don’t charge for failed or cached responses.

Why not cache markdown?

Redis free tier is small and GitHub CDN already caches.

If you can answer these without hesitation, you’re already ahead of 80% of candidates.

Layer 3 — Invariants (this is senior-level)

These are the rules of your system. You must know them:

Invariant 1

Browser never talks to GitHub directly.

If violated → token leak, quota bypass, no control.

Invariant 2

One token = one active session.

If violated → sharing, abuse, quota gaming.

Invariant 3

Quota checked before side effects.

If violated → users charged for failures.

Invariant 4

SPA has zero route remounts.

If violated → duplicate fetches, inconsistent state.

