Bucket 1: Failure & Reliability (most candidates fail here)

These test whether you think about systems under stress.

1. What happens if Redis goes down?

Expected answer:

System cannot validate quota/session

So safest behavior is: block access (fail closed)

Better than allowing uncontrolled GitHub calls

2. What happens if GitHub API is slow or returns 500?

Expected:

Backend returns error

Quota is NOT consumed

User sees blocked / error state

No silent failure

3. What happens if two requests race at the same time?

Expected:

Redis counters are atomic

Pre-check happens before fetch

Only allowed ones pass

4. What if session TTL expires while user is active?

Expected:

Next request refreshes TTL

If expired, treated as new session

Old session lock released

Bucket 2: Security & Abuse (this is your strongest area)

These make you look senior.

5. How do you prevent someone from sharing their token?

Expected:

Token bound to session id

Redis active_session lock

Different browser blocked

6. What if someone inspects network calls and reuses headers?

Expected:

Session id is random per browser

Different environment = blocked

Token alone is insufficient

7. Can someone bypass quotas?

Expected:

No, because all GitHub access is backend gated

Frontend cannot call GitHub directly

8. Why not store token in localStorage?

Expected:

Easier to steal

Session-based approach is safer

Token entry modal + memory storage

Bucket 3: Architecture & Trade-offs (this is staff-level)

These test whether you understand why not something else.

9. Why Redis and not SQL?

Expected:

TTL support

Atomic counters

No relational data

Simple key-value model fits problem

10. Why not cache GitHub responses?

Expected:

Redis free tier small

GitHub CDN already caches

Content freshness vs memory trade-off

11. Why Next.js API instead of separate backend?

Expected:

Same deployment

Lower complexity

Good for gateway-style logic

12. Why not WebSockets / SSE?

Expected:

Read-only system

No real-time requirements

Simpler request-response fits

Bucket 4: Scaling & Evolution (this is where people get stuck)

These show you can think beyond current system.

13. How would you scale this to 1M users?

Expected:

Redis cluster

Token sharding

Rate limits per IP

GitHub API limits become bottleneck

14. What would you change if Redis memory is limited?

Expected:

Evict old quotas

Move lifetime quotas to DB

Keep only active sessions in Redis

15. How would you make this multi-tenant?

Expected:

Different repos per user

Namespace tokens

Isolate quotas per tenant

16. How would you support write access?

Expected:

